==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|condamner|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{term/t|la|condemnāre||to sentence, condemn, blame}}, from {{term|lang=la|com-}} + {{term/t|la|damnāre||to harm, condemn, damn}}, from {{term|lang=la|damnum||damage, injury, loss}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{audio|en-us-condemn.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|ɛm}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To confer some sort of [[eternal]] divine punishment upon.
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To adjudge (a building) as being unfit for habitation.
#: ''The house was '''condemned''' after it was badly damaged by fire.''
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To scold sharply; to excoriate the perpetrators of.
#: ''The president  '''condemns''' the terrorist.''
#: ''The president '''condemns''' the terrorist attacks.''
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To judicially pronounce (someone) guilty.
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To determine and declare (property) to be assigned to public use. See [[eminent domain]]
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To adjudge (food or drink) as being unfit for human consumption.
# {{context|transitive|legal|lang=en}} To declare (a vessel) to be forfeited to the government, to be a prize, or to be unfit for service.

